    <header>
        <h1>Self Introduction for Interview: Complete Guide with Pro Tips</h1>
        <p class="intro">Master your <span class="highlight">self introduction for interview</span> with this step-by-step guide. Learn the perfect structure, essential tips, and best practices to create a strong first impression in every job interview.</p>
    </header>

    <div class="container">

        <div class="section">
            <h2>Why Your Self Introduction Is Important</h2>
            <p>The opening question ‚ÄúTell me about yourself‚Äù or ‚ÄúPlease introduce yourself‚Äù is one of the most common in interviews. Your answer creates the first impression, shows confidence, clarity, structure, and relevance to the role. A strong introduction can set a positive tone for the entire conversation.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="section">
            <h2>Recommended Structure for Self Introduction</h2>
            <p>Use this proven 3-part framework that works in almost every interview:</p>
            <div class="steps-grid">
                <div class="card">
                    <i class="fas fa-user-circle"></i>
                    <h3>1. Present (10‚Äì15 seconds)</h3>
                    <p>Start with your current professional identity / status. Mention your name, current role, highest qualification or most recent position.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="card">
                    <i class="fas fa-history"></i>
                    <h3>2. Past (30‚Äì50 seconds)</h3>
                    <p>Highlight relevant education, work experience, key achievements, and skills that match the job description. Focus only on what is valuable for this role.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="card">
                    <i class="fas fa-rocket"></i>
                    <h3>3. Future (15‚Äì25 seconds)</h3>
                    <p>Explain why you are interested in this position / company and how you can contribute. End with enthusiasm and a smooth transition.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="section">
            <h2>Complete List of Pro Tips for Self Introduction</h2>
            <ul class="tips-list">
                <li>Keep your introduction between 60‚Äì90 seconds ‚Äî never longer than 2 minutes.</li>
                <li>Practice speaking clearly, at a moderate pace with a confident tone.</li>
                <li>Smile naturally and maintain good eye contact (especially in video interviews).</li>
                <li>Customize your introduction for every job ‚Äî use keywords from the job description.</li>
                <li>Focus on professional information only ‚Äî avoid personal details like family, age, hobbies unless directly asked.</li>
                <li>Start strong: Begin with your name and current status clearly and energetically.</li>
                <li>Use action verbs and quantify achievements when possible (increased, reduced, managed, delivered, etc.).</li>
                <li>Avoid memorized robotic delivery ‚Äî speak naturally as if having a conversation.</li>
                <li>End with a bridge sentence that connects your skills to the company‚Äôs needs.</li>
                <li>Do not repeat what is already written in your resume word-for-word.</li>
                <li>Prepare 2‚Äì3 versions: one short (45‚Äì60 sec), one detailed (90 sec), and one very concise (30 sec).</li>
                <li>Record yourself practicing ‚Äî check for filler words (um, ah, like), speed, and clarity.</li>
                <li>Show enthusiasm and genuine interest in the role and company.</li>
                <li>Stay positive ‚Äî never speak negatively about previous employers or experiences.</li>
                <li>Be ready to expand any point if the interviewer asks follow-up questions.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="section">
            <h2>Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>
            <ul class="tips-list" style="counter-reset: tip 0;">
                <li>Giving a very long life story starting from childhood</li>
                <li>Repeating your entire resume chronologically</li>
                <li>Sharing irrelevant personal information</li>
                <li>Using negative language or complaining about past jobs</li>
                <li>Speaking too fast or too softly</li>
                <li>Sounding rehearsed or robotic</li>
                <li>Forgetting to connect your experience to the job requirements</li>
                <li>Ending abruptly without showing interest in the role</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

